import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

drive.mount('/content/drive')

df = pd.read_excel('AirQualityUCI.xlsx')

print("Column types before processing:")
print(df.dtypes)

df['Date_Time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'].astype(str) + ' ' + df['Time'].astype(str))

numeric_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns
df[numeric_cols] = df[numeric_cols].replace(-200, np.nan)

# Drop columns that have more than 30% of their values labeled as missing
threshold = len(df) * 0.7
df = df.dropna(thresh=threshold, axis=1)

df = df.dropna()

df['Hour'] = df['Date_Time'].dt.hour
df['Month'] = df['Date_Time'].dt.month
# Monday=0, Sunday=6
df['Weekday'] = df['Date_Time'].dt.weekday

print("Available columns after cleaning:")
print(df.columns.tolist())

available_pollutants = [col for col in ['CO(GT)', 'NMHC(GT)', 'C6H6(GT)', 'NOx(GT)', 'NO2(GT)']
                       if col in df.columns]
meteorological = ['T', 'RH', 'AH']

analysis_df = df[['Date_Time', 'Hour', 'Month', 'Weekday'] + available_pollutants + meteorological].copy()

print("Final analysis columns:")
print(analysis_df.columns.tolist())
print("First 3 rows:")
print(analysis_df.head(3))

Question 1: What relationships are there between the different types of pollutants?

In[]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

sns.set_style("whitegrid")
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = [12, 8]

corr_matrix = analysis_df[available_pollutants + meteorological].corr()
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', center=0, fmt='.2f')
plt.title('Correlation Between Air Quality Variables')
plt.show()

X = analysis_df[available_pollutants + meteorological].copy()
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

pca = PCA()
principal_components = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(range(1, len(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)+1),
         pca.explained_variance_ratio_, 'bo-', linewidth=2)
plt.title('PCA Scree Plot')
plt.xlabel('Principal Component')
plt.ylabel('Proportion of Variance Explained')
plt.show()

def biplot(score, coeff, labels=None):
    xs = score[:,0]
    ys = score[:,1]
    n = coeff.shape[0]
    scalex = 1.0/(xs.max() - xs.min())
    scaley = 1.0/(ys.max() - ys.min())

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    plt.scatter(xs * scalex, ys * scaley, alpha=0.5)

    for i in range(n):
        plt.arrow(0, 0, coeff[i,0], coeff[i,1], color='r', alpha=0.5)
        plt.text(coeff[i,0]*1.15, coeff[i,1]*1.15, labels[i], color='g', ha='center', va='center')

    plt.xlabel(f"PC1 ({pca.explained_variance_ratio_[0]*100:.1f}%)")
    plt.ylabel(f"PC2 ({pca.explained_variance_ratio_[1]*100:.1f}%)")
    plt.title('PCA Biplot')
    plt.grid()

biplot(principal_components[:,0:2], np.transpose(pca.components_[0:2, :]),
       labels=available_pollutants + meteorological)
plt.show()

print("Correlation matrix between air quality variables:")
print(corr_matrix.round(2))

print("PCA explained variance ratios:")
print(pd.DataFrame({
    'Principal Component': range(1, len(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)+1),
    'Variance Explained': pca.explained_variance_ratio_
}).round(3))

print("PCA component loadings (first 2 components):")
print(pd.DataFrame(pca.components_[0:2].T,
                  index=available_pollutants + meteorological,
                  columns=['PC1', 'PC2']).round(3))

Question 5: What sort of relationship is there between temperature and gas concentrations?

In[]:
import scipy.stats as stats

sns.set_style("whitegrid")
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = [12, 8]

df = pd.read_excel('/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/AirQualityUCI.xlsx')
df['Date_Time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'].astype(str) + ' ' + df['Time'].astype(str))

numeric_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns
df[numeric_cols] = df[numeric_cols].replace(-200, np.nan)

threshold = len(df) * 0.7
df = df.dropna(thresh=threshold, axis=1)
df = df.dropna()

df['Hour'] = df['Date_Time'].dt.hour
df['Month'] = df['Date_Time'].dt.month
df['Weekday'] = df['Date_Time'].dt.weekday

available_pollutants = [col for col in ['CO(GT)', 'NMHC(GT)', 'C6H6(GT)', 'NOx(GT)', 'NO2(GT)'] if col in df.columns]
meteorological = ['T', 'RH', 'AH']

analysis_df = df[['Date_Time', 'Hour', 'Month', 'Weekday'] + available_pollutants + meteorological].copy()

temp_gas_df = analysis_df[['T'] + available_pollutants].dropna()
temp_corr = temp_gas_df.corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(temp_corr[['T']].drop('T'), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', center=0, fmt='.2f')
plt.title('Correlation Between Temperature and Gas Concentrations')
plt.xlabel('Temperature')
plt.ylabel('Gas Type')
plt.show()

print("Temperature-Pollutant Correlation Table:")
print(temp_corr[['T']].drop('T').round(3))

results = []

for gas in available_pollutants:
    slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(
        x=temp_gas_df['T'],
        y=temp_gas_df[gas]
    )

    results.append({
        'Pollutant': gas,
        'Slope': slope,
        'Intercept': intercept,
        'R-value': r_value,
        'P-value': p_value,
        'Std Error': std_err
    })

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.regplot(data=temp_gas_df, x='T', y=gas,
               scatter_kws={'alpha': 0.3},
               line_kws={'color': 'red'})
    plt.title(f'Temperature vs {gas} Concentration')
    plt.xlabel('Temperature (C)')
    plt.ylabel(f'{gas} (mg/m)')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    print(f"{gas} vs Temperature:")
    print(f"  Regression Equation: {gas} = {slope:.3f}*T + {intercept:.3f}")
    print(f"  Correlation (R): {r_value:.3f} (P-value: {p_value:.3g})")
    print(f"  Standard Error: {std_err:.3f}")

results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)
results_df.set_index('Pollutant', inplace=True)

print("SUMMARY REGRESSION STATISTICS:")
print(results_df.round(3))

  • There is no significant relationship between temperature and CO levels.
  • C6H6 levels show a slight increase with temperature.
  • NOx and NO2 concentrations decrease with increasing temperature, likely due to better atmospheric dispersion and possibly changes in human activity or traffic patterns.
